 The hit/effect of the tomato agroindustry on the (away from cities) poor in Mexico 
 Marfa Antonieta Barron, Fernando Rello* 
 Faculty of Money flow, Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico, Mexico DF, Mexico 
 
 Abstract 
 This article faces/deals with the issue of whether the tomato agroindustry (TAl) has been an effective tool in the reduction of 
 (away from cities) poorness. The TAl is by far the most important agroindustry in Mexico in terms of exports and employment creation. Most 
 of the laborers employed by the TAl in northwest Mexico are (lasting for a short time) traveling workers coming from poor areas in 
 southern Mexico. Conditions of poorness-caused traveling are explained. The (features/ qualities/ traits) and plans of large, modern 
 tomato businesses/projects are carefully studied. The main end/end result is that traveling worker income earned in the tomato fields and packing plants, is 
 basic for the bare survival in villages in poor areas. However, this does not provide a solution to poorness 
 help because traveling worker income is not (good) enough to add/give to (transfer of money from individuals to businesses) in the moving communities, or the to 
 create the conditions for endogenous local development.Â© 2000 Published by Elsevier Science B.V. 
 Keywords: Tomato agroindustry; Employment; Traveling; Poorness; Mexico 
 
 1. Introduction 
 This article carefully studies the role of (when lots of countries communicate and talk with each other) and 
 agroindustry in the generation of income and the improvement of living conditions in (away from cities) Mexico. The 
 position one often meets in the available 
 books as well as a position taken by different Latin 
 American governments, is that the export agroindustry is a means of (helping increase/showing in a good way) fair (away from cities) development. It is important therefore to present/cause the following 
 question: has agroindustry in fact been an effective 
 instrument in the reduction of (away from cities) poorness? 
 Unfortunately, there is a low amount of studies carefully studying 
 the effects of agroindustry on (away from cities) poorness. Most of 
 the studies have (focused mental and physical effort) on agroindustrial technology, financing, forms of association, and markets. 
 These studies provide little information on the effects of agroindustry on incomes and employment in 
 * Corresponding author. Present address: Medanos 39, Col. Las 
 Aguilas, 01710 Mexico DF, Mexico. 
 
 poor areas. Some studies, however, have 
 gave/given useful ideas on the labor market (e.g., 
 Wilcox-Young, 1993, for northern Mexico). 
 To deal with this gap in knowledge, we began/tried a 
 study of the tomato agroindustry (TAl) in Mexico, and 
 its hit/effect on employment in poor areas away from cities. The TAl especially, and the (the study of plants) agroindustry in general, are interesting for a few reasons. 
 In general, in terms of output, employment, processing/packing, and exports, (the study of plants) agroindustry is the most important agroindustry in Mexico. 
 According to data from the Ministry of Farming, 
 (the study of plants) makes up/is equal to 18% of Mexico's farming-based 
 production and half of its farming-based exports. Due 
 to the highly labor-intensive nature of (the study of plants) 
 and (plant-related) processing, it creates more than 
 20% of the total labor-days within the Mexican farming-based part/area. More than that, (the study of plants) agroindustry 
 has survived and grew/showed/waved in the current climate of 
 (when lots of countries communicate and talk with each other), and has (branched out/done different things) exports to the US 
 market and increased its scale of production. 
 
