 Especially, the TAl is the most important of the 
 (plant-related) agroindustries. TAl has created a (related to a large area) 
 labor market to which workers are attracted from the 
 country's poor (away from cities) areas. Thousands of 
 native (to) poor (person) workers leave these poor areas 
 every year to labor in the tomato fields in the north of 
 Mexico. 
 Our research question is whether the TAl is adding/giving to poorness help in traveling worker-sending areas, especially, in communities in Oaxaca, which 
 send traveling workers yearly to TAl fields in Sinaloa 
 and Baja California, in the northwest of Mexico. 
 We go ahead as follows. First, we examine labor 
 supply status and the traveling caused by poorness in 
 the Mixteca area and Valles Centrales, both areas 
 being in Oaxaca. Second, we examine the labor market in northern areas where the TAl packers operate, 
 including wages and working and living conditions of 
 the workers' families. Finally, we test the hit/effect of 
 the TAl on the living standards of the Oaxacan poor (person) families that send traveling workers to the TAl areas. 
 
 2. Labor supply created in the poor areas 
 exporting labor 
 We guess that labor supply to Mexican 
 agroindustry coming from not important (away from cities) zones depends, among other things, on the degree of poorness 
 and on the lack of jobs in the sending areas. If 
 poorness (irritates/makes worse) and living conditions break down, 
 then the "push factor" to move will increase, or 
 at least the (reward or reason for doing something) will increase to look (for), outside 
 of farming or outside the sending area, other 
 sources of employment or income that are not to be 
 found within the local (process of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 As a result of the use of (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) (change to make better/related to changing something) programs and (away from cities) reform programs, (away from cities) 
 poorness in Mexico has deepened during the past 
 ten years. At the same time, both internal and external 
 traveling have increased significantly. The number of 
 (away from cities) poor increased during 1984-1992, from 6.7 to 
 8.8 million living in extreme poorness (INEGI-CEPAL, 
 1993). Another study of the "social part/area" of farm-related, both "ejidos" ((person or business who occupies a house, office, etc.) organizations) and other 
 communities, decided that (away from cities) poorness in ejidos 
 is huge. 47.3% of ejido farmers were poor in 1994 
 (de Janvry eta!., 1997). 
 
 There is enough information available in Mexico 
 to decide that the principal response of (away from cities) families to worsening living conditions has been to look (for) 
 an income outside farming on their own farm. 
 This response is also common among farming-based 
 field-workers in other countries. Three surveys have 
 been carried out (not very long ago) on ejido homes, providing 
 information on sources of family income and change 
 in those incomes over time. The first two surveys 
 were carried out in 1990 and 1994, by the Ministry 
 for Land-related Reform. The third was carried out in 
 1997, by the Institute for Land-related Development and 
 the World Bank. Analyses of these data include de 
 Janvry et al. (1997, 1998), Lanjouw (1998), CEPAL 
 (1999), and Davis (1999). 
 Earnings outside own-farming are very important 
 to the poorest (away from cities) families. For example in 1994, 
 small farmers with holdings of less than 2 ha, whose 
 little land placed them among the poorest, earned only 
 18% of their family income from own-farming and 
 animals farming/managing money, whereas their income from other 
 sources (working outside the farming-based part/area and 
 working in wage-employment in the farming-based part/area) amounted to 47% of their total income. Payments from traveling workers to other areas within Mexico, 
 and from people (who leave their own countries) to the US made up another third 
 of their incomes. Yunez-Naude eta!. (1998) reach the 
 same end/end result using general balance models applied to (away from cities) towns in Mexico. This demonstrates the 
 great importance to poor (away from cities) families in Mexico of 
 income from traveling. 
 The areas with high rates of out-traveling, such 
 as our focal area, Oaxaca, are poor and very rare/not enough 
 in natural and workers. They are dependent on 
 low wages from unskilled jobs, and live in barely (easy to get to, use, or understand), poor areas that create very 
 little employment. Poorness rates in these areas are 
 high and increasing. In 1970, 74% of the Mixteca 
 population had an income level of less than twice the 
 minimum wage, which placed them below the poorness 
 line. In 1990, this percentage had grown to 80%. Faced 
 with this danger and the lack of jobs, the response of many families has been to move towards 
 the northwest to work in the vegetable fields. 
 Majority of people/of the group moves. There are 
 whole villages of seasonal traveling workers. A survey 
 carried out in Coatecas (Valles Centrales) points to/shows 
 that 87% of the 217 families surveyed had family 
 
 M.A. Barron, F. Rella/ Farming-based Money flow 23 (2000) 289-297 
 
 members who were traveling workers. Out of these traveling workers, 
 72% went to Sinaloa to work on the tomato and other 
 vegetable fields. This demonstrates the great importance of employment created by the TAl for the poor 
 of Oaxaca (Ortiz, 1998). 
 
 3. TAl, axis of the labor market 
 The high labor needed things demanded by the 
 production and packaging of tomatoes and other vegetables has led to the creation of a wide (related to a large area) 
 market for labor. Guesses made by the Program of 
 Farming-based Day-Workers of the Ministry of Social 
 Development suggest that, in the State of Sinaloa 
 alone, 135 000 traveling worker day-workers crowd together from 
 different areas of Mexico. 
 The demand for work depends on the energy 
 of the (plant-related) business and their technology. The 
 TAl companies, that participate in the labor markets 
 of the northwest are modern, large and (branched out/done different things). 
 They operate in different areas, and in association 
 with other national and foreign companies in both the 
 agroindustrial and (money-related) parts/areas. The largest companies control between 1000 and 2500 ha. These are 
 owned or rented lands, on which they employ the most 
 up-to-date technology. Their owners have become 
 rich exporters. The largest are big businessmen, 
 owners of warehouses in the wholesale markets of 
 Mexico City and Guadalajara. Further details on the 
 TAl can be found in Echanove ( 1999) and Lara and 
 de Grammont (1999). 
 Recent (popular things/general ways things are going) in vegetable production and export 
 point to/show medium-level growth. However, the TAl has increased its size and share of the (the study of plants) part/area. 
 There is also (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of concentration in the TAL 
 One also watches/states increasing (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) in (plant-related) production as part of a business plan 
 to boost penetration of Mexican produce into export 
 markets. According to data from to the Ministry of 
 Farming, 14 (plant-related) varieties were produced 
 in Mexico in the early 1970s, while in 1994 there were 
 more than 80 varieties, some of them fancy and (related to a group of people with the same race, culture, religion, etc.) 
 vegetables. 
 The TAl, (even though there is the existence of) the continuing modernization of 
 its technology, has always been, and continues to be, 
 labor-intensive. All the tasks involved are done manually - seedling production either in (glass buildings where plants are grown) or 
 
 291 
 
 in the fields, planting out cuttings, (producing crops/helping something grow), and 
 collecting. This can be contrasted with the mechanized collecting and packing of processed tomatoes 
 common across the US. Tomatoes are also much 
 more labor-intensive than maize, the main cereal 
 crop. The number of work days per hectare of tomato 
 going along with/matching up to the technology available previous 
 to ferti-crop-watering/rinsing with water is calculated at about 122 days, 
 instead of 29 days needed/demanded for the production 
 of maize. 
 The TAl operates within a big picture  of strong international competition for control of the final markets 
 for (plant-related) produce, within the US and Canada. 
 (related to computers and science) modernization forms part of this commercial fight. Over the last few years, Mexican horticulturists have begun to close the (related to computers and science) failure/mistake 
 that separates them from their competitors, and to 
 introduce both plastic-culture (a way of doing things needing/ordering the planted land to be covered in plastic sheets) 
 and ferti-crop-watering/rinsing with water. Both technologies raise labor needed things per hectare. This is especially so since 
 raising production rates from 30 to 60 or more tons 
 per hectare, increases labor needs for the manual 
 collecting involved. The last thing just mentioned is an unskilled job 
 performed by the traveling workers. Labor needs have 
 also increased for produce-selectors to work in the 
 packing plants. 
 In addition to use of new technology, flexible and ad 
 hoc means of labor organization are being used. For 
 example, more (made to do one thing very well) labor is needed/demanded in view of 
 these new production ways of doing things, in better-paid positions (engineers and technicians) for supervising production. Yet TAl firms continue to use unskilled 
 seasonal traveling worker native (to) workers for collecting, 
 as well as local women in the packing plants. The 
 greater volume of harvest (arising from use of new 
 technologies and resulting increases in working well) is handled by taking on more traveling workers and 
 more women workers. The areas are still hired by the 
 traditional hiring methods. The situation here is, therefore, one of combining modern production technology 
 with old forms of labor organization. 
 It is a great advantage for the TAl to have access to cheap labor that it can employ completely at the 
 convenience of the industry's methods and production rhythms. Field and collecting tasks are carried 
 out by traveling worker native (to) workers. Often these are 
 whole family groups, including the children. They 
 
 292 
 
 M.A. Barron, F. Rello/Agricultural Money flow 23 (2000) 289-297 
 
 are employed on a seasonal basis for the 6 months 
 a year that an farming-based cycle lasts. They are hired 
 for piecework or by the day, but with a said 
 minimum daily (weight/number of tons) to be collected. They are 
 hired for low wages and with hardly any work-related 
 benefits. 
 The basic plan of the TAl consists of combining investment in the most up-to-date technology 
 with the intensive use of cheap labor, and this makes up/is equal to the basis of the TAl's competitive advantage. 
 The possibility of finding workers, at low cost and in 
 the numbers and at the times needed/demanded by the companies, is very important to these companies. 
 Therefore they put into use hiring methods designed to secure/make sure of the supply of labor in the production process. 
 Even though some day-workers arrive in these production areas under their own will, the majority 
 of workers are hired by, or bound to, the companies from the workers' place of origin. As harvest 
 approaches, the employer contracts (people or businesses who buy goods to sell to stores, not you) who 
 travel from Sinaloa to labor-exporting areas in the 
 States of Oaxaca or Guerrero. (people or businesses who buy goods to sell to stores, not you) and buses 
 arrive at a given site on dates known to everyone 
 locally, and begin to select people. When they have 
 got together 50 or 60 workers, they transport them to 
 Sinaloa. 
 Is the TAl an business/project based on cheap labor? 
 Without doubt, the existence of low-cost traveling worker work 
 represents a huge advantage to, and benefit for, such 
 a business. This industry benefits from the flow of 
 poorly paid labor, because it keeps the business's labor costs low while keeping high its competitive level 
 and (money made/good things received). However, the (wanting to beat others in contests) of the TAl 
 does not depend only on (compared to other things) low (moneys paid for working), but 
 also on a well-demonstrated ability to improve its 
 technology and increase its working well. 
 
 4. Recent (popular things/general ways things are going) in labor supply and living 
 conditions 
 Recent (popular things/general ways things are going) in the northwest's labor market are 
 marked by an important fact for traveling workers: labor supply has grown faster than labor demand. The 
 existence of this new process was suggested by the (able to be seen/worthy of attention) increase in new participants to this labor market in 
 1997 as compared to 1995. The group of day-workers 
 moving for the first time to San Quintfn, in the State 
 
 of Baja California, rose from 31 to 44% of the total 
 numberofmigratingmen between 1995 and 1997. The 
 corresponding figures for moving women showed 
 an increase from 29 to 50% (Barron, 1997). The fast 
 growth in labor supply is explained by the (worsening / rusting, crumbling, etc.) in poor (person) farming, and the fast growth 
 in traveling, in response to (away from cities) poorness. Although 
 less quickly than the labor supply, the TAl's labor 
 demand has grown too. The last thing just mentioned is mainly the result of an increase in crop production, which means a 
 greater volume for manual harvest, because of this more labor 
 demand. 
 This situation is equal to a (popular thing/general way things are going) towards saturation of the labor markets. This has significant negative effects on the real wages earned by day-workers, 
 on the hiring methods used by the TAl, and on the living conditions of the day-workers. The TAl has taken 
 advantage of the existence of a more plentiful labor 
 supply to give preference to workers with the most 
 physical strength and experience, and has reduced the 
 hiring of children. At the same time, it has also chosen 
 labor-hiring methods that suggest a more intensive use 
 of the labor force (hiring by piecework). This means 
 of hiring is convenient, in terms of income, to both 
 parties. For the TAl, it shows/indicates a reduction in the total labor cost. The stronger, more able, workers can 
 harvest 100 baskets a day or more, by that/in that way increasing 
 their daily income but at the cost of large amounts of physical expense and of a (too) early or soon (having nothing left/having no strength left) of their 
 work ability (to hold or do something). 
 The situation is one of dangerous work and living conditions. Traveling worker day-workers who reach San 
 Quintfn are lodged in camps that have earthen floors, 
 walls of (with a rippled surface) cardboard, and roofs of the same 
 material or of (with a rippled surface) metal, materials which make 
 the change (to help someone)/place to live and sleep terribly hot in summer and very cold in winter. They have no running water and 
 no latrines. Working conditions are no better. (serving or acting to prevent harm) equipment is lacking, and cases of drunkenness 
 are frequent due to the accidental eating of poisonous 
 farming-based chemicals. However, the National Program for Farming-based Day-Laborers that operates in 
 the area, has made good progress in its attempts 
 to improve the living conditions for traveling workers. 
 It has established creches, health-centers, and schools 
 for very young children. In Sinaloa, the Program's 
 presence has been even stronger, and living conditions 
 have as a result improved. 
 
