 5. Test of the effects of the TAl 
 5. 1. Efj'ect on wages 
 Are day-laborers' wages low? The wages paid by 
 the TAl are just like rates in other areas of commercial farming within Mexico, and therefore they 
 are not low in this respect. However, they are low 
 compared to wages in the manufacturing industry, 
 since industrial workers' wages usually include the 
 legally established benefits, such as Sunday pay, 
 social security, holiday pay and (moneys paid regularly after retirement), none of 
 which is included in the farming-based day-laborer's pay. 
 On an international level, the Mexican farming-based 
 day-laborer is at a clear disadvantage relative to his/her 
 look carefully in (to try to better see something that's unclear)  US or Canada. The farmworker in US earns 
 about US$4.00 per an hour and in Canada 
 CA$6.95, in Mexico this amount would be paid for a 
 day's work. 
 There is a evenness in wages in the areas 
 studied. According to the responses from the 16 people interviewed in Oaxaca, their wages go up and down 
 around 40 Mexican pesos. (There are 9.3 pesos to the 
 US$_$.) These figures occur with those given in the 
 Day-Laborers Program in Culiacan, Sinaloa and by 
 a survey carried out in San Quintin, Baja California 
 in 1997, where the wages went up and down between 40 and 
 50 Mexican pesos (BanÂ·6n, 1997). Higher wages are 
 paid for piecework but they do not compare with 
 those paid for day-labor since they suggest a greater 
 work period. (thing that's almost the same as another thing) in wages over areas could 
 be due to the tomato packers' following almost the same  wage 
 policies and that many tomato packing firms have operations in different areas. Besides, the day-workers 
 work (one after the other) in different areas and know the 
 wages paid in those areas and would not accept a 
 lower wage than that paid in other areas. 
 
 5.2. The hit/effect on employment 
 The main good effect of the TAl on poorness 
 is to be seen in employment creation. This is the 
 TAl's principal (thing that's given/work that's done) to the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) of 
 poor areas, where there is an common 
 lack of valuable things from nature and work. In the Valles Centrales outmigration area, there is a number of 
 small-holdings: 11% of families own less than 1 ha, 
 
 293 
 
 32% have up to 2 ha, and 24% have 3 ha. Most of the 
 area has an bad/unhelpful climate, so farm income is 
 not enough to make happy the family's needs. 1 
 The families have to look for employment outside 
 farming. One choice is craft work (the lie/construction 
 of articles using raw materials from palm trees). According to a survey, 97% of the families have at least 
 one member working at this. However, the income 
 from these manufacturing only covers the (instance of buying something for money) of 
 the family's daily maize consumption. 2 The most important off-farm income comes from traveling labor. 
 The last thing just mentioned is the most important source of family income. The 86% of the 217 families interviewed have 
 members that are traveling workers. In 50% families 
 with traveling workers, 1-3 members are traveling workers, in 35% of 
 the families, 3-6 members are traveling workers, and in 15% 
 more than 7 members are traveling workers. More than half of 
 the population leaves these towns to work. 
 Previous information points to/shows that traveling has 
 speeded up since 1985, the year that marked the 
 Mexican money problem. Before 1980, only 11% of 
 the population interviewed had traveling experience, 
 while starting from 1985 75% of those interviewed 
 began to move. 
 The advantage of traveling workers have in the TAl is 
 that they can find stable employment for many 
 months of the year. That is impossible in the outmigration areas. It is not surprising that the traveling 
 period is long, because a longer period of traveling 
 means a higher conesponding income earned by the 
 workers, and so greater savings to be taken home. 
 The TAl has created a demand for labor that has 
 (used/put into action) significant multiplier effects within the TAl 
 areas. Many workers come from the Sinaloa Singing voices, 
 a poorer area in the hills, but close to the inigated 
 plains, where the tomato crop is spread around. The question 
 is, does the flow of workers from Oaxaca displace the 
 local Sinaloan workers? (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) it does not. There 
 are no records of unemployment in the areas away from the cities of 
 Sinaloa, a state that has a marked money-based energy. 
 If there were an excess of local labor, the TAl businessmen would not have to spend money employing 
 
