 (people or businesses who buy goods to sell to stores, not you) to hire labor from in other places, given that traveling workers receive the same wages as locally-hired 
 day-workers. 
 Another issue is whether the traveling has a negative effect in the outmigration areas, creating labor 
 shortages there. This does not appear to be the case, 
 since the demand for workers is very low there, where 
 the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) is spoiled. Moving poor (person) workers 
 usually return home in time to plant their own survival/income plots. 
 5.3. Effects on income 
 The sample of 217 families carefully studied by Ortfz does 
 not provide enough information to carefully study family income plans nor the hit/effect of income and savings from traveling on poorness levels. To complement 
 the sample, we interviewed 16 traveling worker families from 
 Valles Centrales, Oaxaca, applying a more long/big 
 list of questions than that used by Ortiz. The sample size, 
 though small, is (good) enough as a case study to create 
 guesses for further research. The results are laid 
 out in Tables 1 and 2. 
 
 The interviews showed that the minimum traveling period is 3 months, the most frequent is 6 months, 
 and there are even families who move for 1.5 years 
 at a stretch. This information happens with data from 
 Ortiz's survey that, of 636 traveling workers interviewed, 27% 
 moved for a period of between 2 and 5 months, 66% 
 moved for between 6 and 9 months, and 7% moved for more than 10 months. 
 What are the deciding/figuring out factors of the traveling workers' 
 earnings, and of their savings? The most important 
 factors, in this order, are the length of traveling time, 
 and the number of workers per family. Our data show a 
 strong relationship (0.89) between income and length of time 
 of traveling. Relationship between income and number 
 of family workers is weaker and there is no relationship 
 between income and (moneys paid for working) paid (Table 1). 
 The importance of these two factors has an hit/effect 
 on the amount of savings piled up, as is shown 
 in Table 2. The traveling plan consists of placing 
 on the labor market the greatest possible number of 
 family members, and of moving for the longest time 
 possible without leaving alone (and forgetting) (producing crops/helping something grow) of the family 
 plot of land. This explains why whole families leave, 
 and why they stay away for a few months at a time. 
 
