 The day-workers who move for many months and 
 are unable to return in May to plant their own land, 
 enter into land agreements. 
 On the basis of this information it could be said 
 that there exist at least two family survival/income plans. The first is the most common and consists of the 
 combination of traveling and survival/income farming. 
 Families move some months and come back in time 
 to help grow their plots with survival/income products. The 
 second plan is to move for a longer period and to 
 pile up more savings to be invested later in their 
 community. In this case family plots are rented to relatives or trusted neighbors. 
 The savings piled up by the traveling workers 
 change/differ  according to the traveling plan of each family. However, in all cases the total is big, when 
 the following factors are taken into the process of carefully thinking about something. 
 First, the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) of survival/income farming and the employment sources to be found locally in the workers' 
 places of origin cannot (promise that something will definitely happen or that something will definitely work as described) any family (good) enough 
 income for survival. Second, family spending on food 
 in their places of origin is (compared to other things) low, guessed 
 at 212 Mexican pesos per week (US$22.5), which is 
 5512 pesos per 6-month period for a family of five. 
 
 Almost all the families interviewed saved more than 
 5512 pesos, which means that they can all live for 
 6 months back in their home communities without 
 needing to earn any further income (Table 2). So, the 
 saved savings of the traveling worker day-workers will 
 cover all their basic needs, although at an elemental 
 level of survival/income. 
 The final use to which the traveling worker families put their 
 saved savings shows/tells about the importance of those 
 savings to the families. All of them stated that they 
 spend their savings on food and household expenses, in 
 other words they use their savings for survival. Some 
 families talked about/said that they invested in the redecoration of their homes, the (instance of buying something for money) of animals, (material that makes plants grow better), 
 a control/harness, but only one family talked about/said having used 
 their savings to buy land. The income of these latter 
 families is obviously higher than the income of the 
 families who spend their savings only on food. This 
 establishes a clear relationship between the level of 
 savings and the kind of spending. 
 The information gathered provides ideas of 
 the child labor issue. In the current big picture  of intense 
 commercial competition between Mexican and North 
 American horticulturists, the US horticulturists are 
 
 296 
 
 M.A. Barron, F. Rella/ Farming-based Money flow 23 (2000) 289-297 
 
 pressurizing the governments of the US and Mexico 
 to put into use and enforce rules against child 
 labor, because, according to them, child labor puts 
 US horticulturists at a disadvantage. This argument is 
 false, because the wages paid to the children are the 
 same as wages to adults. On occasion, the adults even 
 help the children fill the said minimum daily 
 needed things in order to wanant those daily wages. 
 In this way, the employment of children does not 
 put Mexican tomato growers in a better competitive 
 position. More than that, child labor is reducing due to 
 the fast growth in adult labor supply. 
 That the TAl agrees to hire minors explains the low 
 level of the dependency coefficient for the families of 
 moving day-workers shown in Table 2. This represents a great advantage to these families in that they 
 can this way (in a big way) raise their earnings. Prohibiting child labor in the tomato fields would represent 
 a extreme blow to the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) of moving families. 
 The National Program of Farming-based Day-Laborers 
 guesses that between 30 and 35% of family income 
 is created by children. However, the employment 
 of children involves big costs to traveling worker families because they cannot attend school. There are no 
 education programs in the working fields for traveling worker 
 children. Besides, working conditions in the fields of 
 Sinaloa and Baja California are hard for the children. 
 5.4. Effects/results/suggestions for (the ability to keep something around, or keep something going) 
 Seasonal traveling does not create conditions for 
 (able to last/helping the planet) money-based development in the sending areas. The greater part of traveling income is still 
 (already decided beforehand to happen) just to secure/make sure of survival. Very little is invested 
 in the natural, physical or workers of these 
 communities. Conditions for endogenous growth of 
 sending-area have not been improved by the traveling. For example, the extra income is not (good) enough for 
 the workers to buy land and (material that makes plants grow better), except in a few 
 cases. The lengthy (not being there; not being present)s also result in neglect 
 of the workers' own land. Family plots are (usually/ in a common and regular way) 
 badly attended due to traveling. The fact that children also move in order to work, means that they do 
 not attend school in any regular manner, causing to continue 
 the high levels of (can't read or write) common in Oaxaca, and 
 the low level of (possible greatness or power) in  workers. 
 This last problem needs to be given special attention. Education is a basic test/list of questions in the matter of 
 
 access to better-paying jobs. Because of their lacking 
 education, the day-workers are criticized to occupying the hardest, worst-paid positions. If the educational level of the children does not improve, they 
 will continue working and earning just the same as 
 their parents, by that/in that way recreating these same conditions 
 of poorness. To summarize, this farming-based big plan/layout/dishonest plan of 
 infra-survival/income traveling work is being caused to continue. 
 It is a non-(able to last/helping the planet) means of job, because it 
 would enter into deep trouble if, for any reason, the traveling 
 flow were intenupted. 
 
 6. Ends/end results 
 First, the employment offered by the TAl is important to the survival of whole villages in Oaxaca, and to 
 other settlements that find themselves trapped in conditions of unemployment and extreme poorness. These 
 jobs offer them an income very hard to get in 
 their poor, not important villages in Oaxaca. 
 Without these earnings, many of these people would 
 already have left alone their home villages, or would 
 be living there under even worse facts or conditions (that surround someone). 
 Second, this good effect is not the result of 
 good wages and work-related benefits given by the 
 TAl, because, as discussed above, wages are low and 
 benefits and working and living conditions are poor, 
 and they represent a (huge, almost shocking, difference between two things) to the earnings and 
 richness of large, modern companies. The positive 
 hit/effect is more the result of the big picture  of extreme 
 poorness in which the traveling workers find themselves, 
 and the lack of energy in the (process of people making, selling, and buying things) of the areas that they come from. Faced with this big picture  of 
 almost no local work other choices, seasonal traveling 
 to the fields of Mexico's northwest is unavoidable, and 
 there is no doable/possible substitute for this. 
 Third, discussions before the signing of NAFTA 
 suggested that the fruit and vegetable production and 
 export part/area was going to bring huge benefits to 
 Mexico. While it is true to say that vegetable exports 
 have proved to be an other choice to (away from cities) unemployment, they cannot resolve the problem of (away from cities) poorness 
 and backwardness, related to deeper (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) factors. 
 Fourth, traveling worker earnings allow the families to survive, but they add/give hardly any capital to the 
 local community. As a result, this income does not 
 add/give towards the creation of local conditions 
 
 M.A. Barron, F. Rella/Agricultural Money flow 23 (2000) 289-297 
 
 starting up endogenous development. It does not represent a synergetic development, which would raise 
 the productive ability (to hold or do something) of the labor-exporting areas 
 in the same way as in the TAl areas. 
 Fifth, it would this way not be unwisely in a rush to suggest that the 
 TAl, which makes big (money made/good things received), assume a larger 
 role in the war on poorness of these traveling worker communities, the very people who have made those (money made/good things received) 
 possible. This would not agree the TAl's (wanting to beat others in contests). This could be done/tried in any of the 
 following ways: (1) cooperating more in educational 
 programs; (2) construction of classrooms; (3) paying 
 teachers who educate the children of traveling worker laborer; 
 (4) improving the living and working conditions of the 
 traveling worker day-workers in the TAl areas. 
 
